# Triage a single GitHub PR

**Inputs**:
- A PR record from `detect-prs.prompt`: `{number, title, body,
  author, created_at, updated_at, labels, base_ref, head_ref,
  additions, deletions, changed_files, is_draft, mergeable,
  raw_lang_hint, cycle_count}`.
- `TRUSTED_GH_USERS` (parsed by the orchestrator from `.env.agent`).
- The project tree (`context/`, `output/`, `output-analysis/`,
  `.project/`, `README.md`, `CLAUDE.md`) — used to interpret which
  area of the project the PR touches.
- `cycle_count` — passed in by the orchestrator (originally
  computed by `detect-prs`). This prompt does NOT recompute it; it
  just echoes the value into the verdict and uses it to choose
  language nuances downstream (e.g. when `cycle_count > 1`, hint
  that the triage notes can mention "this is a follow-up cycle").

**Output**:
`../output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/triage.md`, where `<C>` is
the cycle index passed in by the orchestrator. Single markdown
file. The orchestrator MUST create the cycle subfolder
(`cycle-<C>/`) and any missing parents before invoking this
prompt.

**Skip if**:
`../output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/triage.md` exists AND its
mtime is newer than the PR's `updated_at` AND newer than the
timestamp of the PR's most recent comment or review. Otherwise
re-triage. Note: a new cycle (`C` bumped by `detect-prs`) always
corresponds to a fresh, empty cycle subfolder, so the skip
condition naturally fires only when the same cycle is being re-run
on a stale-free PR.

---

## What this prompt decides

For every PR, produce the following structured verdict:

### 1. Trust

`trusted = (author ∈ TRUSTED_GH_USERS)`. The orchestrator reads the
env var once; this prompt just looks up the boolean.

### 2. Severity

A small ladder. Used for the auto-draft disclaimer (D3) and to
make the summary block scannable. The severity is driven by the
deepest layer of the project the PR touches:

- **`cosmetic`**: only prose / typo / link fixes in non-canonical
  files (e.g. `README.md`, prompt header text, comment-only edits
  to `.project/PROJECT.md`). No semantic change.
- **`spec-detail`**: touches `context-analysis/`, `output/`, or
  `output-analysis/`, OR touches a `context/` file but only at the
  prose / wording / cross-reference level (no requirement / UC /
  actor change). Typical: clarification of an attribute, fix a
  cross-ref, glossary entry.
- **`requirements`**: would add / change / drop a requirement
  (`R1..R10+`) or a use case (`UC-01..UC-09+`). Touches
  `context/03-requirements.md` or `context/04-use-cases.md` in a
  way that affects the canonical list. The disclaimer at the top
  of the draft review is mandatory (D3):
  > *This review was auto-drafted by the project's AI agent —
  > please cross-check with project owner before relying on it.*
- **`architectural`**: introduces a new construct, retires an
  existing one, changes the three-actor model, OR touches
  `.project/decisions/` (an ADR). Same disclaimer applies AND the
  review should be especially conservative ("we will discuss this
  at the next WG before merging").

**Heuristic** (apply in order, first match wins):

1. If any file under `.project/decisions/` is added or modified
   → **architectural**.
2. If `context/03-requirements.md` or `context/04-use-cases.md` is
   modified AND the diff adds / removes / changes a requirement or
   UC entry (not just a cross-ref tweak) → **requirements**. A
   purely additive UC like UC-09 still counts here.
3. If any other `context/*.md` is modified, OR
   `context-analysis/`, `output/`, `output-analysis/` is modified
   → **spec-detail**.
4. Otherwise → **cosmetic**.

When the diff straddles two tiers (e.g. modifies
`context/03-requirements.md` AND `context/99-glossary.md`), pick
the higher tier — severity is the max across files.

### 3. Language

Detect the PR body's natural language. Output an ISO-639-1 code:

- `en` (English)
- `es` (Spanish)
- `pt` (Portuguese)
- `fr` (French)
- `it` (Italian)
- `de` (German)

If detection is inconclusive, ambiguous, or the body is too short
to call (e.g. just a title and one sentence), default to `en` (D4).
The review will then be drafted in English.

Mixed-language bodies (common when the body quotes the spec in
English but the prose around it is Spanish): pick whatever the
PR's own narrative is in, not the quoted spec content.

### 4. Cycle index

Echo the `cycle_count` integer passed in by the orchestrator
(originally computed by `detect-prs` — see its "Cycle counter"
section). `1` means this is the first AI cycle on the PR; `2+`
means the author has pushed new commits or replied to a prior AI
review and the pipeline is preparing a follow-up.

Do NOT recompute the count here. The cycle index is the single
source of truth that `detect-prs` produces; recomputing inside the
triage prompt would risk drift if the comments / reviews list
changes between the two steps.

The anti-loop cap (D5) is enforced upstream: `detect-prs` drops
PRs at `cycle_count >= 4` before they reach this prompt and
applies the `pr:ai-conversation-cap-hit` label itself in `--live`
mode. By the time `triage-pr.prompt` is invoked, the cycle index
is guaranteed to be in `{1, 2, 3}`.

When `cycle_count > 1`, mention in the **Notes for downstream
prompts** section that the review draft must acknowledge the
prior AI review and address the author's new commits or replies
(see `propose-review.prompt`).

### 5. Files touched (grouped by root)

Read the PR's file list and group the paths by their first
directory:

- `context/` — canonical spec content
- `context-analysis/` — pre-spec generated artefacts
- `prompts/` — build scripts
- `output/` — the spec itself
- `output-analysis/` — per-iteration analyses
- `.project/` — governance (PROJECT.md, phases/, decisions/, LOG.md)
- `other` — anything that does not match the above (e.g.
  `README.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.gitignore`)

Used downstream by `analyze-pr` to focus the four axes (e.g. if
`prompts/` is touched, the convention axis pays attention to the
prompt header format).

### 6. Claim summary

One or two sentences paraphrasing what the PR is trying to do.
Lift from the PR body's first paragraph or "## Changes" section
when present. Used by `analyze-pr` and `propose-review` to anchor
their reasoning on the author's own stated intent (which the
scope axis will compare against the actual diff).

## Output format

Write `output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/triage.md` with this
exact shape so the orchestrator can parse the structured fields:

```markdown
# Triage — PR #<N> (cycle <C>)

- title: <verbatim PR title>
- author: <login>
- base_ref: <baseRefName>
- head_ref: <headRefName>
- created_at: <ISO-8601>
- updated_at: <ISO-8601>
- trusted: <true | false>
- severity: <cosmetic | spec-detail | requirements | architectural>
- lang: <en | es | pt | fr | it | de>
- cycle_count: <C>  (1 = first AI cycle on this PR; 2..3 = follow-up)

## Files touched (grouped)

- context/: <comma-separated paths, or "(none)">
- context-analysis/: ...
- prompts/: ...
- output/: ...
- output-analysis/: ...
- .project/: ...
- other: ...

## Claim summary

<1–2 sentences paraphrasing what the PR is trying to do, lifted
from the PR body. Verbatim quotes are fine when they capture the
intent cleanly.>

## Reasoning

<2–4 sentences explaining the severity classification. Cite the
specific files / paths in the diff that drove the decision. If
language detection was a close call, say so.>

## Notes for downstream prompts

<Optional — anything analyze-pr or propose-review should know.
E.g. "diff touches R4.1 as a Note appendix, not a rewrite —
severity stayed at requirements but the change is additive; the
analysis should anchor on the listen-mode termination semantics",
or "author mentions an open thread in PROJECT.md; the review
should cross-check that the thread reference is still live".>
```

Keep the file short — this is a routing decision, not an essay.
Two screens max.
